<tt>Fri Oct  3 20:44:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
You have hit upon one of the very key elements in the evolution of PTSD, as I understand it. Early in the game is when most of the effects of trauma are most easily accessed and treated. Not only do we see this now in the &quot;counselling&quot; given to school age children who have been touched by violence, but in police departments and other professional vocations where trauma, physical and psychological, is a rule. After time, the effects set in, and significant changes occur, like concrete. Ask me, I know.<br><br>
This is NOT a new thing. According to Shay, his analysis of the evidence surviving from the ancient Greek culture clearly shows a structured methodology of &quot;counselling&quot; for returning combat warriors. They deliberately challenged and altered the direction of the warrior's thought to allow the warrior to resume a productive and honored role in society without the dehumanized conduct that frequently tags along for the ride in the absence of such care.<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;We were denied those rights of passage and as a result not only did the Vietnam veteran suffer but so did his loved ones and in the end the shadow of shame has continued to prevail over our nation.&quot; <br><br>
Your words fit.<br><br>
What troubles me deeply is not only were we &quot;denied&quot;, but the reason WHY we were denied. I see in myself that many factors blend in with the unresolved nightmares and flashbacks of the &quot;stressor&quot; events, to contribute to what I experience today, and to what others are subjected by my actions and reactions. I can appear very illogical and violent at times when I am triggered. Progress is that I am beginning to scare myself. <br><br>
This issue and topic is complex. One characteristic is outstanding, however. I do not think that I have any disagreement that PTSD SUCKS! <br><br>
PTSD, the gift that keeps on giving.
